## NASA Goddard Space Flight Center, Space Weather Research Center ( SWRC )
## Message Type: Weekly Space Weather Summary Report for January 24, 2018 - January 30, 2018
##
## Message Issue Date: 2018-01-31T21:50:03Z
## Report Coverage Begin Date: 2018-01-24T00:00Z
## Report Coverage End Date: 2018-01-30T23:59Z
## Message ID: 20180131-7D-001
##
## Disclaimer: NOAA's Space Weather Prediction Center (http://swpc.noaa.gov) is the United States Government official source for space weather forecasts. This "Experimental Research Information" consists of preliminary NASA research products and should be interpreted and used accordingly.


## Summary:

Solar activity was at low level during this reporting period with no significant flares or CMEs.    

Geomagnetic activity was at below minor levels with Kp index (a measure of geomagnetic activity, ranging 0-9) <=4 for the reporting period. The highest value of Kp=4 occurred during the synoptic period of 2018-01-24T21:00Z-24:00Z. This increase in geomagnetic activity was associated with a coronal hole high speed stream detected by DSCOVR/ACE at L1 around 2018-01-24. Solar wind speed reached values of ~500 km/s on 2018-01-26.  

STEREO A IMPACT/PLASTIC instruments detected the arrival of a coronal hole high speed stream around 2018-01-24. Solar wind speed reached values of >600 km/s on 2018-01-27. 

The > 0.8 MeV energetic electron flux detected at GOES remained below the threshold level of 10^5 pfu for the entire reporting period. 

The energetic proton flux of >10 MeV protons detected at GOES and the 13-100 MeV protons at STEREO A were all at background levels for the entire reporting period. 

Space Weather Impact:
Space weather impacts on NASA spacecraft are expected to have been low this week.

##Events:
Flares (M-class and above)
Date         Start     Stop      Peak      Class   Location         
None Observed  

CMEs (>500 km/s):

Earth directed:
Starting time        Speed (km/s)   Type   Direction (LON/LAT in HEEQ)   Half-Angle width (degrees)  Detecting spacecraft (real-time)  
None Observed  

Non-Earth directed:
Starting time        Speed (km/s)   Type   Direction (LON/LAT in HEEQ)   Half-Angle width (degrees)  Detecting spacecraft (real-time)  
None Observed   

## Space Weather Outlook:
## Outlook Coverage Begin Date: 2018-01-31T00:00Z 
## Outlook Coverage End Date:  2018-02-06T23:59Z

Solar activity is expected to be low for the upcoming week. There is only one small active region currently visible on the solar disk that could produce some flares or CMEs. Geomagnetic activity is expected to be low to moderate. A slight increase in geomagnetic activity may occur around 2018-02-05 due to the arrival of a coronal hole high speed stream from the northern coronal hole seen on the Earth's facing solar disk around 2018-01-31.


## Notes: 
SCORE CME typification system:
S-type: CMEs with speeds less than 500 km/s
C-type: Common 500-999 km/s
O-type: Occasional 1000-1999 km/s
R-type: Rare 2000-2999 km/s
ER-type: Extremely Rare >3000 km/s

## Summary:

Solar activity was at low level during this reporting period. There was 1 C-type CME (see details below).   

Geomagnetic activity was at below minor levels with Kp index (a measure of geomagnetic activity, ranging 0-9) <=3 for the reporting period. The highest value of Kp=3 occurred during several synoptic periods on 2018-01-19T03:00Z-09:00Z, 2018-01-20T00:00Z-09:00Z, 2018-01-21T09:00Z-15:00Z, 2018-01-21T18:00Z-24:00Z, 2018-01-22T00:00Z-06:00Z and 2018-01-22T18:00Z-24:00Z.  The slight increase in geomagnetic activity on 2018-01-21 was associated with the arrival of a coronal hole high speed stream detected by DSCOVR/ACE at L1 around 2018-01-21. Solar wind speeds reached values of ~550 km/s on 2018-01-22.  

STEREO A IMPACT/PLASTIC instruments detected the arrival of a coronal hole high speed stream around 2018-01-19. Solar wind speed reached values of 600-650 km/s on 2018-01-19 and 2018-01-20.

The > 0.8 MeV energetic electron flux detected at GOES remained below the threshold level of 10^5 pfu for the entire reporting period. 

The energetic proton flux of >10 MeV protons detected at GOES and the 13-100 MeV protons at STEREO A were all at background levels for the entire reporting period. 

Space Weather Impact:
Space weather impacts on NASA spacecraft are expected to have been low this week.

## Space Weather Outlook:
## Outlook Coverage Begin Date: 2018-01-24T00:00Z 
## Outlook Coverage End Date:  2018-01-30T23:59Z

Solar activity is expected to be low for the upcoming week. There are currently no active regions visible on the solar surface. Geomagnetic activity is expected to be low to moderate for the upcoming week. It may sightly increase around 2018-01-26 due to a small coronal hole high speed stream.

##

## Report Coverage End Date: 2018-01-02T23:59Z

##
## Disclaimer: NOAA's Space Weather Prediction Center (http://swpc.noaa.gov) is the United States Government official source for space weather forecasts. This "Experimental Research Information" consists of preliminary NASA research products and should be interpreted and used accordingly.


## Summary:

Solar activity was at low levels during this reporting period with no significant flares and just one C-type CME (see details below).   

Geomagnetic activity was at minor levels with Kp index (a measure of geomagnetic activity, ranging 0-9) <=4 for the reporting period. The highest value of Kp=4 occurred during the synoptic period of 2018-01-01T03:00Z - 06:00Z. This increase in geomagnetic activity was associated with a coronal hole high speed stream detected by DSCOVR and ACE at L1 on 2017-12-31 at the end of the day. The solar wind speed at DSCOVR reached values of ~500 km/s on 2018-01-01. 

The solar wind speed at STEREO A reached values of ~650 km/s on 2017-12-31 due to another coronal hole.

The > 0.8 MeV energetic electron flux detected at GOES remained below the threshold level of 10^5 pfu for the entire reporting period, but was elevated on 2017-12-27.

The energetic proton flux of >10 MeV protons detected at GOES and the 13-100 MeV protons at STEREO A were all at background levels for the entire reporting period. 


Space Weather Impact:
Space weather impacts on NASA spacecraft are expected to have been very low this week.

Flares (M-class and above)

Earth directed:

## Space Weather Outlook:
## Outlook Coverage Begin Date: 2018-01-03T00:00Z 
## Outlook Coverage End Date:  2018-01-09T23:59Z

Solar activity is expected to be very low for the upcoming week. There are no major active regions on the solar disk. Geomagnetic activity may increase around 2018-01-08 due to an increase in solar wind speed from a coronal hole that has previously produced speeds of up to 650 km/s at STEREO A.
